                  <Text layoutX="54.0" layoutY="359.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="The main building blocks of HTML include elements and tags. Each element is enclosed in angle brackets (e.g., &lt;p&gt; for paragraph) and usually comes in a pair: an opening tag and a closing tag (e.g., &lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;). HTML follows a tree-like structure beginning with the &lt;html&gt; root element, which houses the &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt; sections. The &lt;head&gt; contains metadata (like the title and links to stylesheets), while the &lt;body&gt; holds all the visible content." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
